nodes.bodyText:
The purpose of the [Client|Member|...]ViewUnifiedConnectionManagers was to present the corresponding view of the unified connection manager with the ConnectionManager API. 
It might be the goal, but the actual implementation doesn't implement that goal:

filtering isn't done consistently.
API doesn't match the views.

For example the MemberViewUnifiedServerConnectionManager will not return only members:
 @Override
    public Collection<ServerConnection> getConnections() {
        return unifiedEndpointManager.getConnections();
    }

It will also return clients.
And if you would register for example a connection listener on the MemberViewUnifiedServerConnectionManager and a client connection gets added in the underlying unifiedEndpointManager, the listener will get triggered on this MemberViewUnifiedServerConnectionManager. In short; you think you register for member events, but you will receive all events.
So filtering is ad hoc.
And here is where the API doesn't make any sense. This comes from the ClientViewUnifiedEndpointManager
   @Override
    public ServerConnection getOrConnect(Address address) {
        return unifiedEndpointManager.getOrConnect(address);
    }

It doesn't make any sense for a client view because you can't connect to a client if the connection is missing. Apart from that Views are typically read only; and that isn't the case here.
Apart from being broken, I found the code very difficult to comprehend and I'm one of the main maintainers of the connection logic. So I want to simplify the logic and in some next round come up with a better approach.

